The protocol's connection setup uses a three-way handshake (SYN -> SYN-ACK -> ACK). The server listens on the fixed port(8032) and assigns a new port per connection via the SYN-ACK. Both sides retry until the handshake completes. If the receiver doesn't receive the final ack and instead receives data, the handshake will be treated as completed
Data is added by the client to a buffer which is then read by the sender_handler, split into segments and sent using a sliding window sized to the bandwidth-delay product(bdp), keeping multiple segments in flight at once. The receiver only accepts segments with cumulative ACKs(if last_acked = n, only accept ack = n+1) that also advertise free buffer space. If the buffer fills up the sender pauses. Unacknowledged segments are retransmitted on timeout.
When all data is sent, the sender sends a FIN (5 times to be safe). The receiver replies with a FINACK (also 5 times(great reliability)). The sender waits for the FINACK before finishing. If it times out, the FIN is retransmitted.
